{"title_page": "Joseph E. Brandle", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name=Joseph E. Brandle\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1839|10|8}}\n|death_date={{Death date and age|1909|5|13|1839|10|8}}\n|placeofburial=[[Coldwater, Michigan]]\n|placeofburial_label=Place of burial\n|image=\n|caption=\n|nickname=\n|birth_place=[[Seneca County, Ohio]]\n|death_place= \n|allegiance={{flagicon|United States|1861}} [[United States|United States of America]]\n|branch={{army|USA}}<br/>[[Union Army]]\n|rank=[[Private (rank)|Private]]\n|unit={{Flagicon|Michigan}} [[17th Regiment Michigan Volunteer Infantry]]\n|awards={{Flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n'''Joseph E. Brandle''' (October 8, 1839 \u2013 May 13, 1909) was an [[United States|American]] soldier who received the [[Medal of Honor]] for valor during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Biography==\nBrandle served in the [[American Civil War]] in the [[17th Regiment Michigan Volunteer Infantry]] for the [[Union Army]]. He received the Medal of Honor on July 20, 1897 for his actions at [[Lenoir City, Tennessee]].\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n'''Citation:'''\n\n<blockquote>While color bearer of his regiment, having been twice wounded and the sight of one eye destroyed, still held to the colors until ordered to the rear by his regimental commander.<ref>[http://www.cmohs.org/recipient-detail/142/brandle-joseph-e.php Congressional Medal of Honor Society]</ref></blockquote>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A-F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Find a Grave|5425}}\n*[http://militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=2095 Military Times]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brandle, Joseph E.}}\n[[Category:1839 births]]\n[[Category:1909 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Seneca County, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Union Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:People of Ohio in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name=Joseph E. Brandle\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1839|10|8}}\n|death_date={{Death date and age|1909|5|13|1839|10|8}}\n|placeofburial=[[Coldwater, Michigan]]\n|placeofburial_label=Place of burial\n|image=\n|caption=\n|nickname=\n|birth_place=[[Seneca County, Ohio]]\n|death_place= \n|allegiance={{flagicon|United States|1861}} [[United States|United States of America]]\n|branch={{army|USA}}<br/>[[Union Army]]\n|rank=[[Private (rank)|Private]]\n|unit={{Flagicon|Michigan}} [[17th Michigan Volunteer Infantry Regiment]]\n|awards={{Flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n'''Joseph E. Brandle''' (October 8, 1839 \u2013 May 13, 1909) was an [[United States|American]] soldier who received the [[Medal of Honor]] for valor during the [[American Civil War]].\n\n==Biography==\nBrandle served in the [[American Civil War]] in the [[17th Michigan Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] for the [[Union Army]]. He received the Medal of Honor on July 20, 1897 for his actions at [[Lenoir City, Tennessee]].\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n'''Citation:'''\n\n<blockquote>While color bearer of his regiment, having been twice wounded and the sight of one eye destroyed, still held to the colors until ordered to the rear by his regimental commander.<ref>[http://www.cmohs.org/recipient-detail/142/brandle-joseph-e.php Congressional Medal of Honor Society]</ref></blockquote>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A-F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Find a Grave|5425}}\n*[http://militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=2095 Military Times]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brandle, Joseph E.}}\n[[Category:1839 births]]\n[[Category:1909 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Seneca County, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Union Army soldiers]